% القسم 1: المقدمة
% ============================================================
\section{Introduction}

\subsection{Background and Motivation}

The dominance of English as the lingua franca of computer science and software development has created significant barriers for non-English speakers, particularly in the Arab world where over 400 million people speak Arabic as their native language. Despite the rapid growth of technology adoption in Arab countries, the lack of Arabic-first programming tools has resulted in a substantial skills gap that impedes technological innovation and economic development in the region.

The historical development of programming languages has been predominantly Anglo-centric, beginning with languages like FORTRAN, COBOL, and C in the mid-20th century, and continuing through modern languages such as Python, JavaScript, and Rust. While these languages have become industry standards, their English-based syntax inherently privileges native English speakers and creates additional cognitive overhead for speakers of other languages.

This linguistic barrier is particularly pronounced for Arabic speakers due to several unique challenges:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Script Directionality:} Arabic is written right-to-left (RTL), while most programming tools are designed for left-to-right (LTR) scripts.
    \item \textbf{Character Set:} Arabic uses a non-Latin alphabet with 28 letters that change form based on position in the word.
    \item \textbf{Morphological Complexity:} Arabic has rich morphology with root-and-pattern derivational system.
    \item \textbf{Numerical Systems:} Arabic uses Eastern Arabic numerals (٠١٢٣٤٥٦٧٨٩) alongside Western Arabic numerals.
\end{enumerate}

Research in programming language education has consistently demonstrated that learners acquire programming concepts more efficiently when instruction and tools are available in their native language. A landmark study by Guzdial and Soloway~\cite{guzdial2002} found that students learning to program in their native language showed significantly higher comprehension rates and lower dropout rates compared to those learning in a second language.

\subsection{Previous Attempts at Arabic Programming Languages}

Several attempts have been made to create Arabic programming languages, though none have achieved widespread adoption or provided comprehensive modern development capabilities:

\textbf{Al-Ramz (2008):} An educational language designed for teaching programming concepts to Arabic speakers. While innovative for its time, it lacked modern features including object-oriented programming, web development capabilities, and a JIT compiler.

\textbf{Qalb (2013):} An interpreted language with Arabic keywords that compiled to JavaScript. It suffered from performance limitations due to its interpreted nature and lacked comprehensive standard libraries.

\textbf{Arabix (2015):} A proposed language with Arabic syntax that aimed to compile to multiple targets. The project remained largely conceptual without a working implementation.

These previous efforts shared common limitations: lack of modern compilation techniques, absence of integrated AI capabilities, insufficient standard libraries, and limited tooling support. Al-Marjaa addresses all these limitations while introducing novel features.

\subsection{Contributions of This Paper}

This paper presents Al-Marjaa, a comprehensive Arabic-first programming language that contributes the following innovations:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Native Arabic Syntax:} Complete programming syntax using authentic Arabic keywords (مُتغيّر، دالة، صنف، إذا، لكل) that align with Arabic linguistic patterns.
    
    \item \textbf{5-Tier JIT Compilation:} Implementation of a sophisticated Just-In-Time compiler with tiered optimization achieving 5.08x speedup over baseline interpretation.
    
    \item \textbf{ONNX Integration:} Built-in support for ONNX runtime, enabling seamless deployment of machine learning models within Arabic code.
    
    \item \textbf{Vibe Coding System:} Revolutionary natural language programming capability allowing developers to describe programs in Arabic and generate executable code automatically.
    
    \item \textbf{Comprehensive UI Framework:} A complete framework for building applications with 30+ Arabic-optimized components, RTL layout support, and reactive data binding.
\end{enumerate}

% ============================================================
% القسم 2: الأعمال ذات الصلة
% ============================================================
\section{Related Work}

\subsection{Non-English Programming Languages}

The concept of non-English programming languages has been explored across various linguistic communities. Wenyan-lang~\cite{wenyan2019} demonstrated the feasibility of Classical Chinese syntax for programming, attracting significant community interest with over 18,000 GitHub stars. The Japanese Dolittle language and Russian Rapira showed that localized programming languages can reduce barriers to entry.

However, most of these languages have remained educational tools rather than production-ready systems. Al-Marjaa distinguishes itself by targeting both educational and production use cases with competitive performance characteristics.

\subsection{Natural Language Programming}

Recent advances in large language models have made natural language programming increasingly practical. GitHub Copilot~\cite{copilot2021} and similar systems demonstrate AI-assisted code generation. However, these systems primarily operate with English input and generate code in English-based languages.

Al-Marjaa's Vibe Coding system enables end-to-end Arabic programming, from natural language description to executable Arabic-syntax code, representing a significant advancement in localized programming tools.

\subsection{JIT Compilation Techniques}

Modern JIT compilation techniques have transformed dynamically-typed languages. The PyPy project~\cite{pypy2011} demonstrated 5-10x speedups for Python, while V8 transformed JavaScript performance. Al-Marjaa implements a custom 5-tier JIT compiler optimized for Arabic syntax patterns, achieving comparable performance improvements.

\subsection{Arabic NLP Challenges}

Arabic Natural Language Processing presents unique challenges due to the language's morphological richness and script characteristics. Diab et al.~\cite{arabicnlp2018} documented these challenges, which informed the design of Al-Marjaa's Vibe Coding system and Arabic text processing components.

