% القسم 3: تصميم اللغة
% ============================================================
\section{Language Design}

\subsection{Syntax Principles}

The syntax of Al-Marjaa is designed around three core principles: linguistic authenticity, conceptual clarity, and technical feasibility. Table~\ref{tab:keywords} presents core keywords alongside their English equivalents.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\caption{Core Language Keywords}
\label{tab:keywords}
\begin{tabular}{@{}llll@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Arabic} & \textbf{Transliteration} & \textbf{English} & \textbf{Category} \\
\midrule
مُتغيّر & mutaghayyar & variable & Declaration \\
ثابت & thabit & constant & Declaration \\
دالة & dallah & function & Declaration \\
صنف & sanf & class & Declaration \\
إذا & idha & if & Control Flow \\
وإلا & wa-illa & else & Control Flow \\
لكل & li-kull & for each & Control Flow \\
بينما & baynama & while & Control Flow \\
أرجع & arji' & return & Control Flow \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\subsection{Code Example}

The following example demonstrates Al-Marjaa syntax for a recursive factorial function:

\begin{lstlisting}[caption=Factorial Function in Al-Marjaa]
// دالة حساب المضروب
دالة مضروب(ن) {
    إذا ن <= 1 {
        أرجع 1؛
    }
    أرجع ن * مضروب(ن - 1)؛
}

اطبع(مضروب(5))؛  // الناتج: 120
\end{lstlisting}

\subsection{Type System}

Al-Marjaa implements a dynamic type system with optional static annotations. The primitive types include:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{رقم (number):} Integer and floating-point values
    \item \textbf{نص (text):} Unicode strings with full Arabic support
    \item \textbf{منطق (boolean):} True/false values using حق (true) and باطل (false)
    \item \textbf{قائمة (list):} Ordered collections
    \item \textbf{قاموس (dictionary):} Key-value mappings
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Object-Oriented Features}

Al-Marjaa supports object-oriented programming through classes (صنف), inheritance, and polymorphism:

\begin{lstlisting}[caption=Object-Oriented Example in Al-Marjaa]
صنف حيوان {
    متغير الاسم؛
    
    دالة حيوان(الاسم) {
        هذا.الاسم = الاسم؛
    }
    
    دالة صوت() {
        أرجع "صوت عام"؛
    }
}

صنف كلب: حيوان {
    دالة صوت() {
        أرجع "نباح!"؛
    }
}

متغير كلبي = جديد كلب("بوبي")؛
اطبع(كلبي.صوت())؛  // الناتج: نباح!
\end{lstlisting}

% ============================================================
% القسم 4: التنفيذ
% ============================================================
\section{Implementation}

\subsection{Compiler Architecture}

Al-Marjaa is implemented in Rust, chosen for its performance characteristics, memory safety guarantees, and excellent tooling. The compiler follows a multi-phase architecture:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Lexer:} Handles Arabic text processing including RTL support, Arabic numerals, and diacritics. Performance: $<1$ms per 1000 lines.
    
    \item \textbf{Parser:} Recursive descent parser with error recovery and Arabic error messages. Performance: $<5$ms per 1000 lines.
    
    \item \textbf{Bytecode Compiler:} Transforms AST to stack-based bytecode with 50+ opcodes.
    
    \item \textbf{JIT Compiler:} 5-tier optimization system (see Section~\ref{sec:jit}).
    
    \item \textbf{Virtual Machine:} Stack-based VM with inline caching and parallel garbage collection.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{JIT Compiler Architecture}
\label{sec:jit}

The JIT compiler implements a sophisticated 5-tier compilation strategy:

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\caption{JIT Compilation Tiers}
\label{tab:jit_tiers}
\begin{tabular}{@{}llll@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Tier} & \textbf{Threshold} & \textbf{Optimizations} & \textbf{Use Case} \\
\midrule
Tier 0 & 0 executions & None & One-time code \\
Tier 1 & 50 executions & Direct threading & Warm code \\
Tier 2 & 200 executions & Constant folding & Hot code \\
Tier 3 & 1000 executions & SIMD vectorization & Very hot code \\
Tier 4 & 5000 executions & Tracing JIT & Critical paths \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Key JIT optimizations include:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Hot Spot Detection:} Automatic identification of frequently executed code paths
    \item \textbf{Constant Folding:} Compile-time evaluation of constant expressions
    \item \textbf{Dead Code Elimination:} Removal of unreachable code branches
    \item \textbf{SIMD Vectorization:} Parallel processing of 4 operations simultaneously
    \item \textbf{Inline Caching:} Caching of method lookup results
\end{itemize}

\subsection{ONNX Integration}

Al-Marjaa provides native ONNX runtime integration:

\begin{lstlisting}[caption=ONNX Model Inference in Al-Marjaa]
// تحميل نموذج ONNX
نموذج = أونكس.حمّل("resnet50.onnx")؛

// إنشاء موتر المدخل
موتر مدخل = موتر.عشوائي([1، 3، 224، 224])؛

// تشغيل الاستدلال
نتيجة = نموذج.استدل({"مدخل": مدخل})؛
اطبع(نتيجة["مخرج"])؛
\end{lstlisting}

\subsection{Vibe Coding System}

The Vibe Coding system enables natural language programming in Arabic:

\begin{lstlisting}[caption=Vibe Coding Example]
// الإدخال باللغة الطبيعية
"أنشئ متغير اسم يساوي أحمد"
// ← متغير اسم = "أحمد"؛

"إذا كان العمر أكبر من 18 اطبع بالغ"
// ← إذا العمر > 18 { اطبع("بالغ")؛ }
\end{lstlisting}

The system uses Qwen 2.5 (0.5B parameters) for Arabic text understanding, with a custom pipeline for intent extraction and code generation.

\subsection{UI Framework}

Version 3.2.0 introduces a comprehensive UI framework with:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Layout System:} صف (Row), عمود (Column), شبكة (Grid), مرن (Flex)
    \item \textbf{30+ Components:} Buttons, text inputs, modals, charts, etc.
    \item \textbf{RTL Support:} Automatic right-to-left layout handling
    \item \textbf{Reactive Binding:} قابل\_للملاحظة (Observable) data with automatic UI updates
    \item \textbf{Hijri Calendar:} Support for Islamic date system
\end{itemize}

